From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Zach Marano <zach.marano@chainguard.dev>
Date: Mon, 7 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] param_build: allow NULL buf in push_octet_string for
 zero-length data

OpenSSL 3.6.2 added NULL parameter validation to
OSSL_PARAM_BLD_push_octet_string that rejects buf == NULL even when
bsize == 0. This breaks callers that pass a zero-length octet string
with a NULL pointer, which is a valid and common pattern in C.

In particular, the Go FIPS crypto shim (Microsoft/Go) passes NULL for
empty TLS 1.3 HKDF contexts, causing a panic during every TLS 1.3
handshake.

Relax the check to only reject NULL buf when bsize > 0.
---
 crypto/param_build.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/crypto/param_build.c b/crypto/param_build.c
index abcdef1234..1234abcdef 100644
--- a/crypto/param_build.c
+++ b/crypto/param_build.c
@@ -365,7 +365,7 @@ int OSSL_PARAM_BLD_push_octet_string(OSSL_PARAM_BLD *bld, const char *key,
     OSSL_PARAM_BLD_DEF *pd;
     int secure;

-    if (bld == NULL || key == NULL || buf == NULL) {
+    if (bld == NULL || key == NULL || (buf == NULL && bsize != 0)) {
         ERR_raise(ERR_LIB_CRYPTO, ERR_R_PASSED_NULL_PARAMETER);
         return 0;
     }
